<DOC><DOCNO> AP890327-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-27-89 1141EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     03-27 0264</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0275</SECOND><HEAD>Rebels Say 53 Soldiers Killed, Five Aircraft Shot Down</HEAD><BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Moslem guerrillas killed 53 Afghanarmy troops and shot down five aircraft in fighting aroundAfghanistan's strategic eastern city of Jalalabad, the insurgentsclaimed today.   However, Mohammad Nabi Amani, an Afghan government spokesman inKabul, said 190 insurgents died in the fighting around Jalalabadand that two government soldiers and three civilians were killed.   The contradicting claims could not be independently reconciled.   The guerrilla-run Afghan News Agency said 53 communist troopsdied, 98 were wounded and five deserted in heavy fighting sinceSaturday. Insurgents shot down four helicopters and one airplaneand captured several posts north of Jalalabad, the agency claimed.   It gave no estimate of guerrilla casualties.   The guerrillas said heavy fighting continued around the city ofJalalabad, the airport to the southeast and in suburbs to thenorth. It said the Afghan air force has retaliated with heavybombing, causing many high civilian casualties.   Jalalabad is the target of the guerrillas' first major offensivesince Feb. 15, the date Soviet troops ended nine years ofinvolvement in the Afghan war. Afghan government forces hold thecountry's key cities but guerrillas reportedly control about 90percent of the countryside.   The guerrillas are fighting to oust the communist government andestablish an Islamic republic of Afghanistan.   Afghan officials claim that Pakistani troops, and U.S. and SaudiArabian military advisers, are fighting with the Pakistan-basedguerrillas.   All three countries supply the guerrillas but have denied thattheir military personnel are fighting in Afghanistan.</TEXT></DOC>